---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Types of Baijiu: Sauce, Strong, Light, and Rice Aroma';
const description = 'A practical guide to the main baijiu aroma types and how each style tastes, drinks, and fits different occasions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <header class="article-header"><div class="narrow"><p class="eyebrow">Aroma Types</p><h1>Types of Baijiu</h1><p class="lede">Baijiu is organized by aroma type. Learning this is the fastest way to stop treating every bottle as the same harsh clear liquor.</p></div></header>
  <section class="content"><article>
    <h2>Sauce Aroma</h2><p>Famous through Maotai, sauce-aroma baijiu can be savory, layered, fermented, nutty, and intense. It is prestigious, but not always the easiest entry point.</p>
    <h2>Strong Aroma</h2><p>Often lush, fruity, and expressive. Strong aroma is widely consumed in China and can be easier for some beginners because the fruit and cellar notes feel generous rather than austere.</p>
    <h2>Light Aroma</h2><p>Cleaner, sharper, and more direct. It can be a useful first comparison point for drinkers familiar with clear spirits, though good examples still have grain character.</p>
    <h2>Rice Aroma</h2><p>Usually softer and lower in intensity, often associated with southern China. It can work well for gentle introductions and cocktails.</p>
    <div class="callout">Choose by occasion: sauce aroma for prestige and slow tasting, strong aroma for banquets and expressive flavor, light aroma for cleaner drinking, rice aroma for softer entry points.</div>
  </article></section>
</BaseLayout>
